            <h2>Class I Strong Verbs</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">C</span>lass I verbs have an '<strong>i</strong>' 
                followed by a consonant in the root of the verb. When they conjugate, they follow the vowel change pattern
                <strong>ī - ā - i</strong>. This means that the root vowel in the present is '<strong>ī</strong>',
                the root vowel in the past singular is '<strong>ā</strong>', and the root vowel in the past pural is
                '<strong>i</strong>'. So '<em>ic bite - I bite</em>', becomes '<em>ic bat - I bit</em>' or '<em>hie
                    biton - they bit</em>'.
            </p>
            <p>It is important to note that the '<strong>i</strong>' in the present and past plural
                are not pronounced the same way. The vowel in the present tense and past singular is
                always a long vowel,
                which is indicated by the macron above the letter. These macrons are never present in manuscripts, and
                so will not be included going forward.
                (See the <a href="advpronunciationguide.html" class="darkorange-text">advanced pronunciation guide</a>
                for an explanation of long and short vowels.)</p>
            <p>In addition to the vowel change in the root, verbs also conjugate for person and number as normal.
                Examine the verb '<em>writan</em>' in: '<em>He writ mid his fingre on ðære eorþan - He wrote in the
                    earth with his finger</em>' and '<em>We writaþ be ðæm leode - We write about the people</em>'.
            </p>
